Kenya
has recorded 9 new COVID-19 cases from a sample size of 5,151 tested in the
last 24 hours translating to a 0.2 per cent positivity rate. From
the cases, 8 are Kenyans and one is a foreigner. The youngest case is that of a
31-year-old man while the oldest is a 91-year-old senior citizen. With
the new cases, total confirmed positive infections now stand at 323,204 with 3,448,106
cumulative tests having been conducted so far. According to Health CS
Mutahi Kagwe, the cases were recorded in Nairobi, Nyeri, Turkana and Nakuru
Counties. Nakuru recorded 6 new cases
while the remaining three counties recorded a single case each. “A
total of 17,172,651 vaccines have been administered across the country. Of
these, 7,932,686 are partially vaccinated while those fully vaccinated are
7,854,320. Another 21,120,622 are doses administered to those between 15 to 17
years while 265,023 are booster doses,” Kagwe said in a statement. “The
total number of vaccines administered in the last 24 hours is 33,094 while the
total number of people fully vaccinated in the last 24 hours is 11,284.” Kagwe continued on to
say that 12 persons recovered from the disease in the period under review
pushing total recoveries to 317,503 of whom 264,503 are from the
Home-Based Care and Isolation program, while 53,000 are from various health
facilities countrywide. A
single patient however succumbed to COVID-19, according to Kagwe, bringing cumulative
deaths to 5,647.  “A
total of 21 patients are currently admitted in various health facilities
countrywide, while 129 are under the Home-Based Isolation and Care program. 1
patient is in the Intensive Care Unit (ICU) and is on ventilatory support.
Another 4 patients are on supplemental oxygen and all of them are in the
general wards. No patient is in the High Dependency Unit (HDU),” the Health CS
said.